fraudulent transactions tell a different story — despite having a higher mean of $122.21, their median is just $9.25, meaning the typical fraud transaction is actually smaller than a typical legitimate one. This gap between mean and median in fraud cases indicates that a small number of large fraudulent transactions are inflating the average, while the majority of fraud occurs at very low amounts. This is consistent with a well-known fraud pattern called \"low and slow\", where fraudsters deliberately keep transaction amounts small to avoid triggering bank alerts and detection systems. Further supporting this, the maximum legitimate transaction reaches $25,691 compared to only $2,125 for fraud, confirming that fraudsters rarely attempt high-value transactions. Both distributions are heavily right-skewed, with most transactions clustering near zero regardless of class, which is typical for financial transaction data dominated by small everyday purchases.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Summary stats comparison\namount_stats = data.groupby('Class')['Amount'].agg(['mean', 'median', 'max', 'min', 'std'])\namount_stats.index = ['Legitimate', 'Fraud']\nprint(amount_stats)\n\n# Distribution plot\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))\n\ndata[data['Class'] == 0]['Amount'].plot(kind='hist', bins=50, ax=axes[0], \n                                         title='Legitimate Transaction Amounts', \n                                         color='steelblue', edgecolor='black')\naxes[0].set_xlabel('Amount ($)')\naxes[0].set_ylabel('Frequency')\n\ndata[data['Class'] == 1]['Amount'].plot(kind='hist', bins=50, ax=axes[1], \n                                         title='Fraud Transaction Amounts', \n                                         color='red', edgecolor='black')\naxes[1].set_xlabel('Amount ($)')\naxes[1].set_ylabel('Frequency')\n\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-02-28T10:46:55.219862Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-02-28T10:46:55.220296Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-02-28T10:46:55.834460Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-02-28T10:46:55.220264Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-02-28T10:46:55.833139Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"                  mean  median       max  min         std\nLegitimate   88.291022   22.00  25691.16  0.0  250.105092\nFraud       122.211321    9.25   2125.87  0.0  256.683288\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1400x500 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":13},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Time Analysis\n\nAn analysis of transaction timing reveals a clear and important contrast between legitimate and fraudulent activity throughout the day. Legitimate transactions follow a predictable human behaviour pattern — activity is low in the early morning hours, picks up from around 6am, peaks at 9pm (hour 21) reflecting evening shopping and online purchases, then drops sharply after midnight. Fraudulent transactions, however, tell a completely different story. Fraud peaks at 2am with 57 transactions, followed by another spike at 11am with 53 cases and 18pm with 33 cases. The 2am peak is particularly telling — this is when most cardholders are asleep and unlikely to notice suspicious activity on their accounts, making it a prime window for fraudsters to act undetected. The erratic, spiky nature of the fraud line compared to the smooth curve of legitimate transactions further highlights that fraud does not follow normal human purchasing behaviour, which in itself is a useful signal. From a business perspective, banks could use this insight to apply stricter transaction monitoring and additional authentication steps during late night hours, particularly between midnight and 3am, as a targeted fraud prevention measure.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Convert time from seconds to hours\ndata['Hour'] = (data['Time'] // 3600) % 24\n\n# Count fraud and legitimate transactions by hour\nfraud_by_hour = data[data['Class'] == 1].groupby('Hour').size()\nlegit_by_hour = data[data['Class'] == 0].groupby('Hour').size()\n\n# Plot both on separate charts\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(12, 10))\n\nlegit_by_hour.plot(kind='line', ax=axes[0], color='steelblue', marker='o', linewidth=2)\naxes[0].set_title('Legitimate Transactions by Hour of Day')\naxes[0].set_xlabel('Hour of Day')\naxes[0].set_ylabel('Number of Transactions')\naxes[0].set_xticks(range(0, 24))\n\nfraud_by_hour.plot(kind='line', ax=axes[1], color='red', marker='o', linewidth=2)\naxes[1].set_title('Fraudulent Transactions by Hour of Day')\naxes[1].set_xlabel('Hour of Day')\naxes[1].set_ylabel('Number of Transactions')\naxes[1].set_xticks(range(0, 24))\n\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\n\n# Print peak hours\nprint(\"Peak hour for Legitimate transactions:\", legit_by_hour.idxmax())\nprint(\"Peak hour for Fraud transactions:\", fraud_by_hour.idxmax())\nprint(\"\\nFraud by hour:\\n\", fraud_by_hour.sort_values(ascending=False).head(5))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-02-28T10:56:00.574552Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-02-28T10:56:00.576212Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-02-28T10:56:01.315018Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-02-28T10:56:00.576151Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-02-28T10:56:01.313231Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1200x1000 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"name":"stdout","text":"Peak hour for Legitimate transactions: 21.0\nPeak hour for Fraud transactions: 2.0\n\nFraud by hour:\n Hour\n2.0     57\n11.0    53\n18.0    33\n17.0    29\n15.0    26\ndtype: int64\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":14},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Correlation Analysis\nExamining how each feature relates to fraud reveals which transaction characteristics are most associated with fraudulent behaviour. On the positive side, V11 (0.15), V4 (0.13), and V2 (0.09) show the strongest positive correlations with fraud, meaning higher values in these features tend to appear more frequently in fraudulent transactions. On the negative side, V17 (-0.33), V14 (-0.30), V12 (-0.26), and V10 (-0.22) are the most strongly negatively correlated, meaning unusually low values in these features are a strong signal of potential fraud. V17 in particular stands out as the single most correlated feature with fraud in the entire dataset. It is worth noting that while these correlations exist, none are overwhelmingly strong — the highest absolute correlation is only 0.33 — which reflects the complexity of fraud detection and explains why it cannot be identified by any single feature alone. The heatmap also confirms that the V features are largely independent of each other, shown by the near-zero correlations between them (all off-diagonal values close to 0.00). This is expected given that they were generated through PCA, which by design produces uncorrelated components. From a practical standpoint, features like V17, V14, V12, and V10 would be the first place an analyst or fraud team would look when investigating a suspicious transaction.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Correlation of all features with Class (fraud)\ncorrelation = data.corr()['Class'].sort_values(ascending=False)\nprint(\"Top features positively correlated with Fraud:\")\nprint(correlation[1:8])\nprint(\"\\nTop features negatively correlated with Fraud:\")\nprint(correlation[-7:])\n\n# Heatmap of top correlated features\ntop_pos = correlation[1:8].index.tolist()\ntop_neg = correlation[-7:].index.tolist()\ntop_features = top_pos + top_neg + ['Class']\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))\nsns.heatmap(data[top_features].corr(), \n            annot=True, \n            cmap='coolwarm', \n            fmt='.2f',\n            linewidths=0.5)\nplt.title('Correlation Heatmap — Top Features Related to Fraud')\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-02-28T11:02:29.855924Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-02-28T11:02:29.857122Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-02-28T11:02:31.727606Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-02-28T11:02:29.857081Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-02-28T11:02:31.726317Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Top features positively correlated with Fraud:\nV11    0.154876\nV4     0.133447\nV2     0.091289\nV21    0.040413\nV19    0.034783\nV20    0.020090\nV8     0.019875\nName: Class, dtype: float64\n\nTop features negatively correlated with Fraud:\nV7    -0.187257\nV3    -0.192961\nV16   -0.196539\nV10   -0.216883\nV12   -0.260593\nV14   -0.302544\nV17   -0.326481\nName: Class, dtype: float64\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1400x1000 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":15},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Key Feature Distribution Analysis\nThe boxplots provide the clearest visual evidence yet of what separates fraudulent transactions from legitimate ones. For the negatively correlated features — V17, V14, V12, and V10 — the pattern is consistent and striking: legitimate transactions (blue) cluster tightly around zero, while fraudulent transactions (red) shift dramatically downward into negative territory. V17 shows the most dramatic separation, with the fraud box sitting entirely below -5 while legitimate transactions barely move from zero, making it the single most distinguishable feature in the dataset. V14 and V12 tell a similar story with fraud boxes sitting well below the legitimate baseline. The opposite pattern emerges for positively correlated features — V11 and V4 — where fraudulent transactions shift upward, with fraud boxes sitting considerably higher than their legitimate counterparts, whose values hover near zero. What makes these findings particularly valuable is the limited overlap between the blue and red boxes across most features, meaning these features genuinely separate the two classes rather than being noisy signals. The numerous outlier dots visible in the legitimate class reflect the sheer volume of normal transactions, while the wider fraud boxes indicate more variability in fraudulent behaviour — fraudsters do not all behave the same way. Collectively, these six features form a strong behavioural fingerprint of fraud in this dataset, and any transaction showing simultaneously low V17, V14, V12 and high V11, V4 values should be treated as a high-priority alert.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"top_features = ['V17', 'V14', 'V12', 'V10', 'V11', 'V4']\n\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(16, 10))\naxes = axes.flatten()\n\nfor i, col in enumerate(top_features):\n    sns.boxplot(x='Class', y=col, data=data, \n                ax=axes[i],\n                hue='Class',\n                palette={0: 'steelblue', 1: 'red'},\n                legend=False)\n    axes[i].set_title(f'{col} — Legitimate vs Fraud')\n    axes[i].set_xticklabels(['Legitimate', 'Fraud'])\n    axes[i].set_xlabel('')\n\nplt.suptitle('Key Features — Legitimate vs Fraudulent Transactions', \n             fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', y=1.02)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-02-28T11:17:58.095083Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-02-28T11:17:58.095481Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-02-28T11:18:02.498260Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-02-28T11:17:58.095449Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-02-28T11:18:02.497274Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stderr","text":"/tmp/ipykernel_55/3373197221.py:13: UserWarning: set_ticklabels() should only be used with a fixed number of ticks, i.e. after set_ticks() or using a FixedLocator.\n  axes[i].set_xticklabels(['Legitimate', 'Fraud'])\n/tmp/ipykernel_55/3373197221.py:13: UserWarning: set_ticklabels() should only be used with a fixed number of ticks, i.e. after set_ticks() or using a FixedLocator.\n  axes[i].set_xtickl